(Asimov's Three Laws of Robotics were designed as universal constraints for any thinking machine) Tj
T*
(powerful enough to harm us: A robot may not injure a human being or, through inaction, allow a) Tj
T*
(human being to come to harm. A robot must obey the orders given it by human beings except where) Tj
T*
(such orders would conflict with the First Law. A robot must protect its own existence as long) Tj
T*
(as such protection does not conflict with the First or Second Law. On paper, the logic is) Tj
T*
(flawless. You could even express it as a function: func isAsimovCompliant\(willAllowHarmToHuman) Tj
T*
(bool, ...\) bool { if willAllowHarmToHuman { return false } ... return true } The main property) Tj
T*
(of this function is that it is a hard constraint. No matter what input you feed the system, the) Tj
T*
(law either permits or forbids the action deterministically, every time. The rules don't bend.) Tj
T*
(We don't have humanoids walking among us just yet, despite Elon's promises. But we have modern) Tj
T*
(generative AI. Our guardrails are delivered as system prompts, text prepended to every) Tj
T*
(conversation before you type a word. They might say "be helpful," "don't produce harmful) Tj
T*
(content," or even "follow Asimov's Three Laws." The problem is that these ins...) Tj
